Scotland's independent schools maintain outstanding academic results and this continued in 2018 with yet another set of outstanding test results, which are only reinforced by individual and collective progress in sport, art, music and other societal engagements.
With up to 30 000 students in Scotland, schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible service for their students and their parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further education, their chosen career and their role as global citizens.
As an education sector capable of designing and implementing adapted curricula, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and inquired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes to his heart."
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we create relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year's test results show that languages are at the top of the list, with a maximum number of approved results in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received A in the final higher grade.
Data collected from SCIS 74 member schools showed that 72 per cent of students who studied mandarin received an A in Higher Grade, and 72 per cent of those who studied German, 69 per cent of those who studied French, and 63 per cent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as crucial skills such as children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language as a subject selection is now considered as important as natural knowledge, technology, engineering knowledge and mathematics on curriculum in independent schools and beyond.
A study carried out by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 concluded that employers were unable to fill their vacancies for various reasons, by 17 per cent, which was attributed to a lack of skills in languages.
With this said, language skills become all more necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
With an increasing number of future jobs requiring language skills, these skills become necessary in a globalised world.
Whatever their career choice, they will have a real advantage in the future if they have adopted a second language.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries, a multilingual person automatically gives a competitive advantage.
According to a survey of over 4,000 adult British published by YouGov 2013, 75 percent said they could not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation in it, and where French was the only language that came up in a two-digit percentage (15 percent).
Therefore, it is so important to invest in language education for our children.
To be able to speak multiple languages, especially those used in developing countries, gives your child a better chance of finding meaningful employment in the future.
In Scotland, each school learns different combinations of languages.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach in languages considered most important for the United Kingdom for 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from within independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools strive to provide a teaching environment that will prepare children and have them with the skills needed to succeed, regardless of what the future holds.
In a global economic environment, it is undoubtedly language that continues to be crucial for the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered as "international communication capacity".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
