While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to an approach divided into stages for the nuclear power that would lead to North Korea being rewarded when it took gradual steps, his statement seemed significant, because it did not reject a unilateral nuclear solution entirely as Pyongyang has previously done.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a seated American president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on 12 June, where Kim promised to work towards "the decommissioning of nuclear weapons on the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has been seeking a formal end to the Korean war in 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first remove its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused negotiations to alleviate severe international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on "destruction first" and increases the pressure by means of sanctions to achieve its objective by coercion and even object to the "declaration to end the war", says Ri.
"The idea that sanctions can get us on our knees is a wishful dream for those people who don't know about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions deepen our distrust."
Ri did not mention plans for a second Kim/Trump Summit, which was highlighted by the US leaders in the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the Minister pointed out three meetings between Kim and South Korea's leader Moon Jae-in over the last five months and added: "If the party to this issue of nuclear disarmament was South Korea and not the United States, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula would not have come to such a deadlock."
Yet the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea's future ability to reach the USA's mainland with rockets was inevitable after "Mr. Evil President" Trump called Kim a "rocketman" on a suicide mission.
This year in the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "all destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take measures to disarm, but it said that much work still remains and that sanctions have to remain until North Korea is disarmed.
