Algflower: The tails decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from Florida's Fisheries and Wild Commission shows a general decrease in algal flowering concentrations for parts of the area around Tampa Bay.
According to the Commission, uneven blooms are reported in the areas around the large municipalities of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier.
The algal flower extends over 20 miles of the coast, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee.
Flicker can be seen about a mile and a half out into the sea outside the big municipality Hillsborough, but in fewer places compared to last week.
Algflowering has also been observed in the large municipality of Pasco.
Medium concentrations in or off the coast of Pinellas have been reported during the past week. Outside the Hillsborough coast low to high concentrations, background concentrations to high concentrations in Manatee, background concentrations to high concentrations in or off the coast of Sarasota, background concentrations to medium-high concentrations in or off the coast of Lee, and low concentrations in Collier.
Reports of respiratory irritation continue to come from the large municipalities of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There were no reports of respiratory irritation in northwestern Florida that past week.
